[[Image:Pachecodemelo.jpg|thumb|right]]
'''José Andrés Pacheco de Melo''' (17 October 1779 &ndash; approx. 1820) was an [[Argentina|Argentine]] statesman and priest. He was a representative to the [[Congress of Tucumán]] which on 9 July 1816 [[Argentine Declaration of Independence|declared the Independence of Argentina]].
Pacheco de Melo was born in [[Salta]] and studied there alongside [[Martín Güemes]]. He entered the [[seminary]] of Our Lady of Loreto in [[Córdoba, Argentina|Córdoba]] and was ordained in 1801 by Bishop Moscoso of [[San Miguel de Tucumán|Tucumán]].
Pacheco de Melo became a priest in [[Livi-Livi]] in [[Chichas]] (now [[Bolivia]]) and used his position to assist the revolutionary forces in [[Alto Perú]]. He was elected by Chichas to the [[San Miguel de Tucumán|Tucumán]] Congress and served in 1816 for the declaration, although there had been a long debate about the legitimacy of his election.
After the Congress moved to [[Buenos Aires]] Pacheco de Melo chaired it in 1818. He subsequently served as a government minister in [[Mendoza, Argentina|Mendoza]]. His death is unclear, believed to have been in 1820 [https://web.archive.org/web/20070311124013/http://www.me.gov.ar/efeme/9dejulio/pacheco.html], and Urquidi notes that he died in Chichas.
