In [[theology]], '''ponerology''' (from Greek ''poneros'', "evil") is a study of [[evil]]. Major subdivisions of the study are the nature of evil, the origin of evil, and evil in relation to the Divine Government.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=The Presbyterian Review|date=1881|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qQEFAAAAQAAJ|page=423|accessdate=2014-10-18}}</ref>

[[Karl Immanuel Nitzsch]] outlined his ''System der christlichen Lehre'' (''System of Christian Doctrine'') into three major rubrics: [[Agathology]], or the Doctrine of the Good; Ponerology, or Doctrine of the Bad; and [[Soteriology]], or the Doctrine of Salvation. He further subdivided ponerology into the topics of [[Sin]] and of [[Death]]<ref name="google2">{{cite book|title=The Methodist Review|date=1895|volume=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdMWAQAAIAAJ|page=203|accessdate=2014-10-18}}</ref><ref name="google3">{{cite book|title=System of Christian doctrine|author=Nitzsch, C.I.|date=1849|publisher=T. & T. Clark|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pMktAAAAYAAJ|page=130|accessdate=2014-10-18}}</ref>

